          ">
          <p>Really interesting approach, nice to see how far you can push S3 plus containers.</p>

<p>That said, I wouldn’t go as far as saying this replaces <strong>AWS Transfer Family</strong> for most use cases. It feels more like a classic DIY vs managed service trade-off.</p>

<p>On pricing, totally fair point. If you’re running something lightweight with low traffic, the ECS or Fargate plus SFTP route will almost always be cheaper on paper compared to the roughly $0.30 per hour endpoint cost. No disagreement there.</p>

<p>But that comparison is really just infrastructure cost, not the full picture. <strong>With the DIY setup, you are now owning scaling, patching, high availability, SSH key management, monitoring, and handling failures when things break.</strong> That is where the cost and risk quietly shifts to your team.</p>

<p><strong>Where AWS Transfer Family still makes a lot of sense is when you need something production ready. Secure by default, multi AZ, integrated with IAM, audit ready, and supporting protocols beyond SFTP like AS2 for B2B or EDI use cases.</strong></p>

<p><strong>So I would frame it more as</strong> <strong>Great option for simple, cost sensitive workloads</strong><br>
But <strong>managed services still win for enterprise, partner facing, and compliance heavy scenarios</strong></p>


